description.text:
This is a camera that is made from the standard USB Camera Module (such as ELP) but it has a hole prepared to accept a standard 12mm lens.

To use the camera module you have to remove any other lens holder. You will also need to tap the plastic with a 12mm/0.5mm tap. It may be possible to jam a lens in but it's really designed to be tapped.

There are no mounting holes on the standard unit. The second base has an attached mount with 2" spaced mounting holes. It's easy enough to drill holes for a mount if you want to do it that way - there's lots of free space inside.

It requires 4 m2 (2mm) nuts and bolts to put together (although you don't need the nuts if you only put it together once or twice). I considered a snap-together but wanted something really secure since this is part of a machine that shakes.

Note: the third image with the serious bracket shows an additional circular holder that's not in the posted bracket.

title: Solar Finder Scope for Hotshoe on Camera

description.text:
ATTENTION:
ONLY POINT YOUR CAMERA AT THE SUN WITH APPROPRIATE PROTECTION!
DO NOT TRY TO LOOK DIRECTLY AT THE SUN!
DO NOT TRY TO LOOK THROUGH THIS FINDER WHEN POINTED AT THE SUN! - It's only intended for indirect pointing.
OTHERWISE YOUR CAMERA OR YOUR EYES MAY BE DAMAGED SEVERELY!
ONLY USE THIS PRINT AT YOUR OWN RISK!

This solar finder may be attached to a standard hotshoe of a camera. It helps finding the sun especially with long focal length lenses. The sun shines on a circular screen through a small hole. This creates a dot of light on the screen. Move the camera until the dot is close to the center of the screen. Then the camera is roughly pointed at the sun.
The long separator between finder and hotshoe helps with long diameter lenses and solar filters.
I recommend using bright filaments (e.g. white). Then the screen will be translucent, making pointing the camera at the sun even easier than by looking through the holes at the sides. See pictures for both ways of using it.

  1. Obtain 4x M3x14 flat head bolts (e.g. McMaster-Carr part number 92125A133), and 4x M3 nylock nuts (e.g. McMaster-Carr part number 90576A102)
  2. Print the left and right halves, and two of the clamps. Make sure to print the phone holder halves with the gluing surfaces upwards so that they will be strong in the dimension that the phone rests in.
  3. Finish the pieces. Use a sanding block to file down the gluing surfaces, and round over any sharp edges.
  4. If the nuts are not loose fits into the nut captures on the clamps, use the M3 bolts to pull them in.
  5. If needed, drill out the screw holes in the caddy and in the clamps to 3.5mm.
  6. Weld (or glue, if you used PLA) the two halves of the phone caddy together. I use this ABS cement from Amazon. Wait a few hours for it to dry. Use tape or a clamp to hold the halves together.
  7. Attach the caddy to the wheelchair. I recommend putting the screws on the end of your Allen wrench, then sticking the screw and the wrench through the large holes on the side. Make sure to get the screws tight into the nuts, but not so tight that you split the plastic!
  8. (optional): If you do not use a phone case, line the bottom of the caddy with foam tape or rubber tape to keep the phone from getting scratched up.

Just a simple alignment tool for the Z-Axis of the Prusa i3 Style Printers, since after every pressure on the axis (e.g. when changing filament) causes a misaligment of the Z-Axis when the stepper motors are undriven. Especially when the printer uses trapezoidal thread rod with a slope of 8mm/revolution (like Anet A8).
I use this after every filament change so I neither have to relevel my bed nor do I need the autolevel sensor.
Print two of them, one for each side.

  1. Auto-Home Axis
  2. Disable Steppers over the menu
  3. Turn both Z-Axis rods by hand until the tool fits underneath
  4. Turn each Z-Axis rod until it lays on the tool with a slightly touch
  5. Remove Tool and start to print

title: Slic3r Configuration - Monoprice Delta Mini Printer

description.text:
UPDATE 9Aug2017: More testing. I need to tweak temperatures to reduce stringing, but the revision 1 profile seems to work very well overall. The picture is a build of my Art Deco Fountain Pen Drying Stand (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2334018)

UPDATE 7Aug2017: Revision 1 includes the following changes:

  • Revised the prime loop. It's now 3mm from the part perimeter, rather than 6mm.
  • Added a 2mm brim for adhesion
  • Changed the autolevel method from basic to P2 (verbose). Also tweaked the Z offset to 0.35mm, which provides a good balance between adhesion and removal on my machine.
  • Hotend heats up after the autolevel. Worked well for me, and doesn't leave divots in the bed.
  • Hotend starting temperature is no longer hard coded.
  • Increased some speeds, which seemed fine on my machine
    Look for MP_MiniDelta_r1.ini. The file 20mm_box_with_hole_MiniDelta.gcode is a sliced example. I've removed the older sliced examples, but the revision 0 ini file is still there if you want it!

UPDATE 3Aug2017: Initial testing looks pretty good, with the caveat that things really stick to the bed. I hope to do some additional tests over the next few days, and post an update.

Here's a basic configuration for the Prusa edition of Slic3r 1.36.1, set up for the Monoprice Delta Mini Printer. This version of Slic3r allows advanced setting for retraction, and the configuration takes advantage of this. It's quite basic everywhere else.

Attached is a test STL 9 tooth gear, and a sliced gcode file. Also attached is a sliced copy of the calibration vector (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:109114) for testing.

Please let me know if you have problems with the config - it's working all right for me, but I just received the printer.

comments.text: I haven't given it a good test yet,  just got it installed last night. But no, I haven't worked out a great string prevention technique yet. Mostly I retract 6 mm quickly (600mm/min) at first, then perform the rest of the retraction (with my old Y that was 110mm) more slowly. Seemed to work fine for me. My big trouble was the filament getting hung up inside the Y splitter where the push fitting screwed in because the internal diameter was too large, and left a small gap before the push fitting. I'm thinking this design will work much better.
comments.author: dagnall53

comments.text:
The best string free retraction I have seen pushed the tip back into the melt for a very little bit after the fast initial retract.. Trouble was I did this by hand and have not been able to create a precise and repeatable mechanical sequence to get the same effect. I'm hoping that my force measurement system will allow me to eventually measure exactly what's going on so I can write the correct sequence of push pull. For now I'm trying to overcome a print bed levelling issue (I think) that is (again I think) causing warp on large prints.
Re the 6mm fittings.. I usually put a chamfer on the entry to guide the filament in.. ( or the fittings already have a small chamfer) ..
It may be that by chance this is a better smooth entry approach than is possible with the smaller diameter 5mm fittings?

  • Print 'handle_base'. I recommend a minimum of 15% fill.

  • Print 'accessory clamp'. I recommend a minimum of 20% fill.

Works quite well I must say, although the the code ended up with some hardcoded values, which I don't really like. However, I thought, I put it up anyway. The keypad probably won't change much anyway, as otherwise I would like it to be more configurable. But, beeing based on the parametic "Simple Keypad" thing, some parts can be changed quite easly anyway. Eventually, I want to mount this somewhere I also have the LCD display... for instance, like this: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:21677 or like this http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18597 ... but for now, those clunky legs will suffice... :) Also, hopefully someone will make a derivate and add some extra information for the buttons somehow. Such as arrows or something... :)

Everything is nicely set up in the .stl file, so just run it through your favorite gcode generator. Then use 4x 30mm M3 scews (and M3 nuts if you want, as the legs have a hole made for one) to assemble the top and legs together. In case you want to print parts individually, you can load it up in Blender, and split it up there by going into edit mode (TAB key), select a vertex (right click), press CTRL+L, and then "p" and press Enter to a separate the selection as a new object. Then you can just exit edit mode by pressing TAB again, select the object and export as a new .stl file. The .scad file it somewhat messy because of hardcoded values, and the generated .stl file needs to be edited as objects will be at different heights. Again, this is because I'm basing this on another thing and didn't want to fiddle around too much on it. Also, for the rotary thing, you can just print this http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:20513 and use defaults in the .scad file. I did in the image, although I would recomend making the base circle of it like 1 or 2 mm less in diameter, as it touches the screw in the corner when rotating...

description.text:
The Thing:
A heat bed wiring fastener that helps provide mechanical support to preserve the integrity of the solder joints.

To Print:
1x Heatbed Clip
2x Heatbed Clip Bar

Vitamins:
Small bolts and nuts to secure the parts together. I used Nylon Lock Nuts Screw Fastener Zinc Plated Black Hex Insert Female M3x0.5mm and M3x14mm Screw Cap Point Hex Socket Screws Bolts.
Epoxy

How to Use:
1). Thread wires through gap in "Heatbed Clip"
2). Position "Heatbed Clip" such that it gently presses the wires against the edge of the heat bed and temporarily clamp it in place
3). Solder wires to the appropriate terminals on the heat bed
4). Screw "Heatbed Clip Bar" onto wires against "Heatbed Clip" using the holes closer to the heat bed. Tighten until the wires cannot move easily. Repeat with distal holes.
5). If satisfied with solder joints and positioning of all parts, epoxy the "Heatbed Clip" to the bottom of the heat bed. Clamp in place until dry.
6). Happy printing!

The Story:
After burning out the original heat bed wiring I tried replacing it with 10 gauge threaded wire, which admittedly was a bit excessive but satisfying. Unfortunately, such thick wire was somewhat stiff and after around twenty hours printing snapped the heatbed terminals despite my attempt to offset the mechanical stress using zipties and looping the wires around the existing heatbed connector. As such, I had to resolder the leads directly to the heatbed, but that left me with no mechanical support whatsoever. To address this issue, I CADed and printed this assembly (on a different printer). After 30 hours it has suffered no apparent strain.

Potential Improvements:
I'm most worried about the epoxy eventually failing due to thermal stresses. A good improvement would be providing a structural means to secure the assembly to the heatbed without infringing upon the heatbed surface while remaining thin underneath to avoid collisions with y-axis motor. My original prototype attempted to fasten itself to the screws connecting the heat bed to the T-bar but proved unstable with a tendency to sag and jam on the y-axis motor. As such I removed it and settled for epoxy, but would be happy to see someone succeed in fastening the assembly with a structural rather than adhesive means.

I like it because it is really a gadget but very easy to use.

It is a really simple design of a fidget toy featuring Cherry MX key switches.
I'll upload some more pictures after I got one of those MX sample switches set to add more tactile variation to it.

The picture represents 0.15mm layer width which is more than enough and it looks good.

The mounting hole for the key switch can be done tighter and less feature rich but with this design it fits and is easy to remove again. I added a picture with five keys assembled, it's still hard to see all detail but might help

Assembly

There is no need to cut anything from the switches ( like support structure or pins ) but you have to keep attention about the orientation when plugging your key switches in.
